title: Milford boys run to state berth
text:
Ty Masco continued to lead the way for the Milford boys’ cross country team Oct. 15, winning the District C3 meet and helping the team earn a spot at the state meet Friday, Oct. 23. 
Masco finished the 5K course in 16:10.07, winning by 50 seconds. 
“Only a few others ran faster,” Coach Michele Kontor said. “He ran 30 seconds faster than last year.” 
She said five of the six runners set personal best times on the course at the Elks Golf Course in Hastings. 
Zach Danekas broke 18 minutes for the first time, finishing in 17:22.21 and fifth place. 
Teammate Hunter Jensen wasn’t far behind, placing sixth in 17:24.65. Kontor said Danekas outkicked Jensen at the end of the race. 
The two Eagle freshmen, Zach Pauley and Beau Hines, broke 19 minutes and finished 29th and 30th, respectively. 
As a team, the Eagles were second behind Minden. 
“We’re disappointed yes, but we qualified,” Kontor said. 
She expects the Eagles to be in contention for another state championship Friday. Masco and Jensen have run at state all four years, while Danekas has been in the field three times and Aidan Pauley, who finished 35th, has run at state twice. 
Aidan Pauley has been battling health issues and was in a lot of pain over the first mile and then panicked a little, Kontor said. 
“Everyone else picked it up,” she said. 
Minden, Columbus Scotus, Mitchell and Sidney also have solid teams that will challenge the Eagles. 
“So many things can happen at state,” Kontor said. “There’s a lot of stress, but it’s exhilarating because it’s state.” 
The Eagles will run at 1 p.m. Friday, Oct. 23, at Kearney Country Club. 
The Milford girls didn’t have the same success at districts. Milford’s top finisher, Savannah Bontrager, was 17th, with Abbie Reitz finishing 18th and Hayley Bogue 20th. 
Kontor said Bontrager improved her time by almost a minute, but still finished in the same position. 
She said Reitz was very disappointed because she felt she could run well enough to make the state field. 
Dani Gropp finished 26th, Hannah Compton 27th and Kaylee Scdoris 28th. 
“We ran the race we wanted,” Kontor said, adding that Boone Central/Newman Grove, which won the girls’ team title, is the top team in the state. 
Milford finished fourth in the team standings.
